lopsidedWins.lopsidedExplain:
The lopsided wins test compares the win margins of the two parties. In states that are gerrymandered, the party that benefits from the gerrymander will win many seats by small margins, while the opposing party wins a few seats by overwhelming margins. The differences in win margins can be calculated using the two-sample t-test, the most widely used test in all of the sciences.

Unfortunately, the two-sample t-test requires that both parties win at least two seats, and DEMOCRATIC won 1 in DE in 2016.

reportService.consistentExplain:
The consistent advantage test compares the median Democratic vote share across all districts to the average (arithmetic mean) Democratic vote share in DE in 2016. If the median is larger than the average, the state may be a Democratic gerrymander. If the median is smaller than the average, the state may be a Republican gerrymander. 
In DE in 2016, the median Democratic vote share was 56.0%, the average Democratic vote share was 56.0%, and the difference is 0.00%. 
It's important to note that when one party is dominant statewide(here is DE), the mean-median difference becomes less reliable. In that case, other tests for asymmetric advantage may be used, as described in Prof. Wang's Election Law Journal article.

consistentAdvantage.consistentExplain:

In DE in 2016, the median Democratic vote share was 56.0%, the average Democratic vote share was 56.0%, and the difference is 0.00%. 
It's important to note that when one party is dominant statewide(here is DE), the mean-median difference becomes less reliable. In that case, other tests for asymmetric advantage may be used, as described in Prof. Wang's Election Law Journal article.

efficiencyGap.efficiencyExplain:
The efficiency gap test counts the number of votes each party wastes in an election to determine whether either party enjoyed a systematic advantage in turning votes into seats. Here we do calculation using margins for Democratic in DE in 2016. If the absolute value of efficiency gap is greater than 8 percent, the state may be a partisian gerrymander. A positive efficiency gap value indicates that Democratic has an advantage; a negative value indicates that Democratic is disadvantaged. 
In DE in 2016, the seat margin for Democratic was 100.0%, the vote margin for Democratic was 56.0%, and the efficiency gap is 37.93%.
It's important to note that when one party is dominant statewide(here is DE), the efficiency gap becomes less reliable. In that case, other tests for asymmetric advantage may be used, as described in Prof. Wang's Election Law Journal article.

reportService.excessExplain:
By comparing DE in 2016 to all Congressional elections carried out in 2016, we can estimate the number of seats Democrats and Republicans might be expected to win. A large deviation from this expected value is not itself evidence of partisan gerrymandering because differences could be caused by any number of factors, but it can be combined with the lopsided wins test and the mean-median difference to estimate the effects of a possible partisan gerrymander. In DE in 2016, Democrats won 1 out of 1 seats with 56.0% of the statewide vote. Our simulations indicate that, according to nationwide trends in 2016, Democrats would be expected to win 0.526 seats.

The difference of -0.474 does not suggest DE was gerrymandered.

The difference of 2.683 does not suggest SC was gerrymandered.

reportService.consistentExplain:
The consistent advantage test compares the median Democratic vote share across all districts to the average (arithmetic mean) Democratic vote share in SD in 2016. If the median is larger than the average, the state may be a Democratic gerrymander. If the median is smaller than the average, the state may be a Republican gerrymander. 
In SD in 2016, the median Democratic vote share was 34.0%, the average Democratic vote share was 34.0%, and the difference is 0.00%. 
It's important to note that when one party is dominant statewide(here is SD), the mean-median difference becomes less reliable. In that case, other tests for asymmetric advantage may be used, as described in Prof. Wang's Election Law Journal article.

lopsidedWins.lopsidedExplain:

A large deviation from this expected value is not itself evidence of partisan gerrymandering because differences could be caused by any number of factors, but it can be combined with the lopsided wins test and the mean-median difference to estimate the effects of a possible partisan gerrymander. In MI in 2014, Democrats won 12 out of 14 seats with 58.5% of the statewide vote. Our simulations indicate that, according to nationwide trends in 2014, Democrats would be expected to win 7.366 seats.

The difference of -4.634 is inconsistent with nationwide trends, and suggests that MI may have been gerrymandered to gain an advantage for DEMOCRATIC.

lopsidedWins.lopsidedExplain:
The lopsided wins test compares the win margins of the two parties. In states that are gerrymandered, the party that benefits from the gerrymander will win many seats by small margins, while the opposing party wins a few seats by overwhelming margins. The differences in win margins can be calculated using the two-sample t-test, the most widely used test in all of the sciences.

Unfortunately, the two-sample t-test requires that both parties win at least two seats, and REPUBLICAN won 8 in UT in 2014.

reportService.consistentExplain:
The consistent advantage test compares the median Democratic vote share across all districts to the average (arithmetic mean) Democratic vote share in UT in 2014. If the median is larger than the average, the state may be a Democratic gerrymander. If the median is smaller than the average, the state may be a Republican gerrymander. 
In UT in 2014, the median Democratic vote share was 35.0%, the average Democratic vote share was 35.6%, and the difference is 0.60%. 
It's important to note that when one party is dominant statewide(here is UT), the mean-median difference becomes less reliable. In that case, other tests for asymmetric advantage may be used, as described in Prof. Wang's Election Law Journal article.

efficiencyGap.efficiencyExplain:

Here we do calculation using margins for Democratic in UT in 2014. If the absolute value of efficiency gap is greater than 8 percent, the state may be a partisian gerrymander. A positive efficiency gap value indicates that Democratic has an advantage; a negative value indicates that Democratic is disadvantaged. 
In UT in 2014, the seat margin for Democratic was 0.0%, the vote margin for Democratic was 35.6%, and the efficiency gap is -21.24%.
It's important to note that when one party is dominant statewide(here is UT), the efficiency gap becomes less reliable. In that case, other tests for asymmetric advantage may be used, as described in Prof. Wang's Election Law Journal article.

A large deviation from this expected value is not itself evidence of partisan gerrymandering because differences could be caused by any number of factors, but it can be combined with the lopsided wins test and the mean-median difference to estimate the effects of a possible partisan gerrymander. In NH in 2014, Democrats won 2 out of 2 seats with 54.9% of the statewide vote. Our simulations indicate that, according to nationwide trends in 2014, Democrats would be expected to win 1.052 seats.

The difference of -0.948 does not suggest NH was gerrymandered.

lopsidedWins.lopsidedExplain:
The lopsided wins test compares the win margins of the two parties. In states that are gerrymandered, the party that benefits from the gerrymander will win many seats by small margins, while the opposing party wins a few seats by overwhelming margins. The differences in win margins can be calculated using the two-sample t-test, the most widely used test in all of the sciences.

 In NJ's 2014 election, Republicans won their districts with an average of 23.33% percent of the vote, and Democrats won their districts with an average of 34.67% percent of the vote. The difference between the two parties’ win margins indicates NJ may be gerrymandered to gain an advantage for REPUBLICAN. The chance that this difference would have arisen by nonpartisan processes alone is 4.9136e-02.

reportService.consistentExplain:
The consistent advantage test compares the median Democratic vote share across all districts to the average (arithmetic mean) Democratic vote share in NJ in 2014. If the median is larger than the average, the state may be a Democratic gerrymander. If the median is smaller than the average, the state may be a Republican gerrymander. 
In NJ in 2014, the median Democratic vote share was 56.5%, the average Democratic vote share was 59.2%, and the difference is 2.70%. This difference does not suggests NJ is gerrymandered.

efficiencyGap.efficiencyExplain:
The efficiency gap test counts the number of votes each party wastes in an election to determine whether either party enjoyed a systematic advantage in turning votes into seats. Here we do calculation using margins for Democratic in NJ in 2014. If the absolute value of efficiency gap is greater than 8 percent, the state may be a partisian gerrymander. A positive efficiency gap value indicates that Democratic has an advantage; a negative value indicates that Democratic is disadvantaged. 
In NJ in 2014, the seat margin for Democratic was 125.0%, the vote margin for Democratic was 59.2%, and the efficiency gap is 56.62%. This efficiency gap suggests NJ is gerrymandered to gain an advantage for DEMOCRATIC.

Here we do calculation using margins for Democratic in OR in 2014. If the absolute value of efficiency gap is greater than 8 percent, the state may be a partisian gerrymander. A positive efficiency gap value indicates that Democratic has an advantage; a negative value indicates that Democratic is disadvantaged. 
In OR in 2014, the seat margin for Democratic was 160.0%, the vote margin for Democratic was 58.3%, and the efficiency gap is 93.47%. This efficiency gap suggests OR is gerrymandered to gain an advantage for DEMOCRATIC.

reportService.excessExplain:
By comparing OR in 2014 to all Congressional elections carried out in 2014, we can estimate the number of seats Democrats and Republicans might be expected to win. A large deviation from this expected value is not itself evidence of partisan gerrymandering because differences could be caused by any number of factors, but it can be combined with the lopsided wins test and the mean-median difference to estimate the effects of a possible partisan gerrymander. In OR in 2014, Democrats won 4 out of 5 seats with 58.3% of the statewide vote. Our simulations indicate that, according to nationwide trends in 2014, Democrats would be expected to win 2.631 seats.

The difference of -1.369 does not suggest OR was gerrymandered.

lopsidedWins.lopsidedExplain:
The lopsided wins test compares the win margins of the two parties. In states that are gerrymandered, the party that benefits from the gerrymander will win many seats by small margins, while the opposing party wins a few seats by overwhelming margins. The differences in win margins can be calculated using the two-sample t-test, the most widely used test in all of the sciences.

Unfortunately, the two-sample t-test requires that both parties win at least two seats, and REPUBLICAN won 6 in KS in 2014.

reportService.consistentExplain:
The consistent advantage test compares the median Democratic vote share across all districts to the average (arithmetic mean) Democratic vote share in KS in 2014. If the median is larger than the average, the state may be a Democratic gerrymander. If the median is smaller than the average, the state may be a Republican gerrymander. 
In KS in 2014, the median Democratic vote share was 43.2%, the average Democratic vote share was 41.9%, and the difference is -1.36%. This difference does not suggests KS is gerrymandered.
